defaultRelationships between defaultPCdefaultCdefaults defaultand Panelsdefault&#xa0;
default1
default4
default.
default              
defaultThe findings of the research commissioned by the LGA ha
defaultve
default indicated that the success or failure of 
defaultPanels 
defaultis dependent on the relationship between PCCs, their offices and Panels. In many cases these relationships are good and provide a sound basis for effective scrutiny. Where relationships have been more difficult if appears to stem from mutual misunderstandings about the Panel’s role. 
default&#xa0;
defaultSuspensions and dismissalsdefault&#xa0;
default1
default5
default.
default              
defaultFor some
default,
default the first year has been challenging
default, particularly where Commissioners chose to suspend or dismiss a Chief Constable. 
defaultThe 
defaultexperience
default 
defaultof Lincolnshire
default, where the Chief Constable was suspended
default will be very instructive for Panels and PCCs alike.
default 
defaultThe Lincolnshire case 
defaulthighlight
defaults
default the 
defaultrelatively
default limited powers that Panels have in such circumstances. 
defaultPanels must be notified of a suspension, but no specific action is prescribed in the legislation. In this first year
default,
default Panels have been on their own in determining what action to take
default in these cases
default. 
default&#xa0;
default1
default6
default.
default              
defaultThe 
defaultGwent example where, as the HASC report states
default,
default “
defaultMrs Napier was persuaded to retire voluntarily before the [scrutiny] process was initiated
default,
default”
default highlights the relative ease with which PCCs are able to circumvent what are already limited
default formal
default powers of scrutiny.
default&#xa0;
default1
default7
default.
default              
defaultThroughout this first year
default,
default Panels have come to realise that the formal powers, such as they are, have at best been of little use and in some 
defaultcases have hindered 
defaultthe function of scrutiny to question and expose and to engage the public in these processes. 
default&#xa0;
default1
default8
default.
default              
defaultThe Panel in Lincolnshire has now undertaken a substantial review of the circumstances surrounding the suspension of Chief Constable Rhodes by the PCC and its own actions in response to the suspension. The findings will be very instructive for both Panels and PCCs.
